		<title>Sereact Raises $110M to Scale AI Robotics Platform</title>
		<link>https://ventureburn.com/sereact-raises-110m-to-scale-ai-robotics-platform/</link>
		
		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Ekemini]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 27 Apr 2026 13:29:05 +0000</pubDate>
				<category><![CDATA[News]]></category>
		<category><![CDATA[Venture Capital]]></category>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://ventureburn.com/?p=200365</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[<p>Sereact has raised $110 million in a Series B funding round. The investment, led by international venture firm Headline, marks a pivotal moment for the company as it transitions from</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/sereact-raises-110m-to-scale-ai-robotics-platform/" data-wpel-link="internal">Sereact Raises $110M to Scale AI Robotics Platform</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a href="https://sereact.ai/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener external noreferrer" data-wpel-link="external"><span style="font-weight: 400">Sereact </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">has raised $110 million in a Series B </span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/qumulusai-secures-45m-to-scale-ai-infrastructure/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400">funding </span></a><span style="font-weight: 400">round. The investment, led by international venture firm Headline, marks a pivotal moment for the company as it transitions from a logistics-focused software provider to a universal &#8220;brain&#8221; for the next generation of autonomous and humanoid robots.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The round attracted new investors, Bullhound Capital, Felix Capital and Daphni. Existing backers Creandum, Air Street Capital and Point Nine also participated. Just 15 months after a €25 million Series A, the funding illustrates how fast the robotics AI market is growing. </span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">From Logistics to Physical Reasoning</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">Founded in 2021 by AI researchers Ralf Gulde and Marc Tuscher, Sereact has differentiated itself through a software-first approach. While many competitors focus on building hardware, Sereact builds vision-language-action models (VLAMs) that enable any robot to see, reason, and act.</span></p>
<div id="attachment_200366" style="width: 1034px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img decoding="async" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-200366" class="size-large wp-image-200366" src="https://ventureburn.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/A-white-robot-1024x770.jpg" alt="A white robot" width="1024" height="770" /><p id="caption-attachment-200366" class="wp-caption-text">Source: Unsplash</p></div>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The centrepiece of this new funding is the launch of Cortex 2.0. Unlike traditional industrial robots that follow rigid, pre-programmed scripts, Cortex 2.0 enables robots to perform consequence prediction. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">By simulating multiple outcomes in a fraction of a second, the robot can choose the action most likely to succeed, such as adjusting a grip on a crushed box or navigating a cluttered workspace without human intervention.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;We bet early that you can’t build real robotics AI in a lab,&#8221; said Ralf Gulde, CEO and co-founder of Sereact. &#8220;You build it with a data flywheel fed by real deployments. We are moving from robots that simply follow instructions to robots that actually understand the physical world.&#8221;</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">More News:</span><a href="https://ventureburn.com/qumulusai-secures-45m-to-scale-ai-infrastructure/" data-wpel-link="internal"><span style="font-weight: 400"> QumulusAI Secures $45M to Scale AI Infrastructure</span></a></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">The Power of Real-World Data</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company’s growth is anchored by its massive self-reinforcing loop. Sereact’s software is already live in over 200 systems across Europe, powering operations for industrial giants like BMW, Daimler Truck, PepsiCo, and H&amp;M. To date, the platform has processed over one billion production &#8220;picks&#8221;, providing a wealth of real-world training data that simulated environments simply cannot match.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">This real-world edge is what Sereact believes will allow it to win in the burgeoning humanoid robot market. With companies including Tesla, Boston Dynamics and Figure AI racing to produce it, the need for hardware-agnostic software that can handle unsupervised tasks has become the industry&#8217;s holy grail.</span></p>
<h2><span style="font-weight: 400">Strategic Expansion into the U.S.</span></h2>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company has just raised $110 million of new capital, and Sereact is looking to take over the world. Much of this investment will be used to set up a U.S. headquarters in Boston as a centre of robotics excellence. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">The company will spend heavily on hiring engineers and commercial specialists to maintain the company&#8217;s presence across North American manufacturing and warehouse environments. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-weight: 400">&#8220;Sereact is doing for robotics what the operating system did for the PC,&#8221; said a spokesperson from Headline. &#8220;By decoupling the intelligence from the hardware, they are making automation accessible to every industry, regardless of what robot they use.&#8221;</span></p>
<p>The post <a href="https://ventureburn.com/sereact-raises-110m-to-scale-ai-robotics-platform/" data-wpel-link="internal">Sereact Raises $110M to Scale AI Robotics Platform</a> appeared first on <a href="https://ventureburn.com" data-wpel-link="internal">Ventureburn</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
			</item>
